parameters.name: bootmode
parameters.doc: Boot mode(s) to apply the parameter to.  Either 'all' (default) to use the parameter on all boots (normal and recovery mode), 'normal' for just normal boots or 'recovery' for just recovery boots.

properties.name: value
properties.doc: Value of the parameter if applicable.  Many parameters are just keywords so this must be left blank, while others (e.g. 'vga') will take a value.

parameters.name: name
parameters.doc: The name of the setting, or a unique string if `condition` given.

parameters.name: key
parameters.doc:
Overrides setting name to prevent resource conflicts if `condition` is
given.

parameters.name: target
parameters.doc:
The file in which to store the settings, defaults to
`/etc/ssh/sshd_config`.

parameters.name: condition
parameters.doc:
Match group condition for the entry,
in the format:

    sshd_config { 'PermitRootLogin':
      value     => 'without-password',
      condition => 'Host example.net',
    }

The value can contain multiple conditions, concatenated together with
whitespace.  This is used if the `Match` block has multiple criteria.

    condition => 'Host example.net User root'

properties.name: value

providers.name: augeas
providers.doc: Uses Augeas API to update an sshd_config parameter

types.name: sshd_config
types.doc:
Manages settings in an OpenSSH sshd_config file.

The resource name is used for the setting name, but if the `condition` is
given, then the name can be something else and the `key` given as the name
of the setting.

Subsystem entries are not managed by this type. There is a specific `sshd_config_subsystem` type to manage these entries.

parameters.name: variable
parameters.doc: The name of the variable, e.g. OPTIONS

parameters.name: quoted
parameters.doc:
Quoting method to use, defaults to `auto`.

* `auto` will quote only if necessary, leaving existing quotes as-is
* `double` and `single` will always quotes
* `none` will remove quotes, which may result in save failures

parameters.name: target
parameters.doc: The file in which to store the variable.

properties.name: value
properties.doc: Value to change the variable to.

properties.name: comment
properties.doc: Text to be stored in a comment immediately above the entry.  It will be automatically prepended with the name of the variable in order for the provider to know whether it controls the comment or not.
